<section xml:id="sec-isom-mystery-isometries" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Mystery Isometries</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Given two congruent figures, what is the isometry that maps one 
            onto the other? In this section, we will learn how to identify the
            type of isometry for this mapping and 
            to construct the axis of a reflection, the center and 
            angle of a rotation, and a vector of a translation or glide 
            reflection. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
        <subsection xml:id="subsec-Isom-mystery-review">
            <title>Review of Isometries</title>
            <p>
                We know that an isometry is a transformation (or function) that 
                preserves the measures of lines and angles.  The original object and its 
                image under an isometry are always congruent to each other.  It turns out 
                if we are given any two congruent figures in the plane there is an isometry 
                that maps one of the figures onto the other.  At the end of this section, 
                you will be given a pair of congruent figures and then will determine the 
                associated isometry using the properties you identified in the early part of 
                the lab.
            </p>
        <exploration>
            <title>Isometry Review and Tools</title>
            <task>
                <title>Orientation Review</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Orientation is a good way of distinguishing between types of 
                        isometries, especially rotations and glide reflections.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In <xref ref="check-orient"/>, which triangle has the 
                        same orientation as <m>\Delta ABC</m>?
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="check-orient">
                        <caption>Orientation of Images of <m>\Delta ABC</m></caption>
                        <image source="orient-check.png">
                            <shortdescription>
                                Triangles ABC, C'A'B', and
                                C1,B1,A1 are shown.
                            </shortdescription>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        Triangle <m>\Delta C'A'B' </m> has the same orientation as 
                        <m>\Delta ABC</m>. Triangle <m>\Delta C'_1 B'_1 A'_1</m> has 
                        the opposite orientation.
                    </p>
                </answer>
            </task>
            <task>
                <title>Fixed Point Review</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Sometimes we can tell which points are fixed and use that 
                        to identify the type of isometry.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        Of the types of isometries studied thus far, 
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    which type has no fixed points?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    which type has exactly one fixed point?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    which type fixes all points that lie on a 
                                    single line?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
