            <task>
                <title>Review of Glide Reflections</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A glide reflection is a two-step isometry.  We first translate by a vector and 
                        then we reflect across the line containing (or parallel to) that vector.  
                        The GeoGebra interactive <xref ref="fig-glideref-rev-mystery"/> shows the original triangle 
                        <m>\Delta ABC</m> and its final image <m>A''B''C''</m> after a reflection across line <m>\overleftrightarrow{DE}</m>
                        and translation by vector <m>\overrightarrow{DE}</m>. Answer the following questions:
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    A glide reflection <fillin characters="5"/> the orientation 
                                    of the figure.
                                    <ul marker="circle">
                                        <li>
                                            maintains
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            reverses
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    The glide reflection image in <xref ref="fig-glideref-rev-mystery"/> 
                                    was produced by reflecting the triangle across line <m>\overleftrightarrow{DE}</m>
                                    and then translating by vector <m>\overrightarrow{DE}</m>.  Do you get the 
                                    same result if you translate by vector <m>\overrightarrow{DE}</m> first and then 
                                    reflect across line <m>\overleftrightarrow{DE}</m>?
                                    <ul marker="circle">
                                        <li>
                                            yes
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            no
                                        </li>
                                        <li>
                                            sometimes but not always
                                        </li>
                                    </ul>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    On the sketch construct the midpoints of each of the segments 
                                    from a vertex <m>P</m> of <m>\Delta ABC</m> to its final image <m>P''</m>
                                    on <m>\Delta A''B''C''</m>.  What information do these midpoints 
                                    give you?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    What strategy could you use to find the reflecting line and 
                                    translation vector for a glide reflection if you only have 
                                    the original figure and final image?
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="fig-glideref-rev-mystery">
                        <caption>
                          An interactive GeoGebra applet for analyzing a glide reflection.
                        </caption>
                        <interactive xml:id="mystery-rev-glideref-app"
                          platform="geogebra">
                          <slate surface="geogebra" material="fyn8nzqe"/>
                        </interactive>
                      </figure>
                </statement>
            </task>
